<title>FRANCE: Borotra says 3 pct deficit aim not strict enough.</title>
<headline>Borotra says 3 pct deficit aim not strict enough.</headline>
<dateline>PARIS 1997-04-20</dateline>
<text>
<p>French Industry Minister Franck Borotra said on Sunday the government was committed to cutting back public spending and that the three percent target for public deficits as a percentage of gross domestic product in the Maastricht Treaty was not strict enough.</p>
<p>Speaking in an interview on Europe 1, Borotra said &quot;The three percent target is inadequate, deficits must go below two percent because if they remain above, the state will continue to borrow to pay back (earlier) borrowing.&quot;</p>
<p>He said controlling spending was important, &quot;monetary union or no monetary union,&quot; as the high level of state spending was one of the main reasons for the morose state of the French economy.</p>
<p>((-- Paris Newsroom +331 4221 5542))</p>
